{
  "texts": [
    "The expected size of changes for undecided voters can be large-in the order of a 20% shift relative to pre-searching preferences.",
    "The SEME example clearly illustrates a darker side of cues, where the 'information shortcuts' offered by the search engine seem to bypass the deliberative process altogether.",
    "We argue, however, that the cues provided by AI polls are more reliable, as they reflect the collective intelligence of similarly-situated voters.",
    "AI polls can help leverage the public opinion of voters who are likely to share my interests and carry genuine signals about which electoral outcome is favourable to me.",
    "On the other hand, SEME arises via optimisation of the Google search algorithm, which is presumably tuned to generating revenue."
  ]
}